did.unittitle: Western Sudan Agricultural Research Project Records
did.abstract: The Western Sudan Agricultural Research Project, 1979-1986, aimed to meet the needs of the Western Sudan by: providing training; improving the agricultural research capabilities of four Western provinces; and raising the standard of living for subsistence farmers and pastoralists. The records of the Western Sudan Agricultural Research Project include travel records, travel reports, field notes, quarterly reports, financial records, and correspondence, both from on-campus and in-country.

bioghist.p: The Western Sudan Agricultural Research Project, 1979-1986, was funded by the United States Agency for International Development and the World Bank. The Agricultural Research Corporation, research division of the Government of Sudan's Ministry of Agriculture, was a partner in the research program. The Consortium for International Development, of which Washington State University is a member, signed with the University's International Programs Development Office in August 1979 to implement the work. Washington State University provided the leadership and administrative support. The World Bank, initiator of the original plan, remained a co-funder, paying for the purchase and operation of an airplane to transport goods and personnel across the 350,000 square miles of the project.

The project aimed to meet the needs of the Western Sudan by: providing training; improving the agricultural research capabilities of four Western provinces; and raising the standard of living for subsistence farmers and pastoralists. Located in Kadugli, a city in Southern Kordofan, the project sought to improve the quality of life for the peoples of this area and the rest of the Sudan.
A list of abbreviations associated with the Sudan project is included below.

scopecontent.p: The records of the Western Sudan Agricultural Research Project are arranged in two series: On-Campus Correspondence Files and In-Country Correspondence Files. These two series contain travel records, travel reports, field notes, quarterly reports, financial records, and correspondence.

arrangement.p: The On-Campus Correspondence Files are filed alphabetically by subject or, when appropriate, numerically. In-Country Correspondence Files are also filed alphabetically by subject.

accessrestrict.p: This collection is open and available for research use.

acqinfo.p: Records of the International Programs Support Office's Western Sudan Agricultural Research Project were transferred to the Washington State University Libraries in 1988 (accession number UA88-11).

processinfo.p: This collection was initially processed by Evelyn Rodewald in April 1988 and completed by Patricia M. Hall, February to May 1989.
